\subsubsection{Unwrapping of Fixpoints is Confluent but not Noetherian}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:unwrap-confluent}
The rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Suppose that $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$ for distinct redexes within $e$.
  
  If the redexes are disjoint, then \cref{lem:disjoint} applies.

  Otherwise, without loss of generality assume the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ contains the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$;
  let $e$ must be of the form |C_1^[mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf])]| ($\alpha$-conversion may be used to ensure that $x$ and $y$ are distinct variables).

  Then |e_1 = C_1^[substNP (C_2^[mu y hnf]) x (mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf]))]|
  and |e_2 = C_1^[mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)])]|.

  From |e_2| we can take just one more \rulename{u-unwrap} step, using the outermost redex |mu x (C_2^[cdots])|, obtaining |e' = C_1^[subst (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]) x (mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]))]|.

  \skewtodo{More to come.}

  Thus we have $\rsteps{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$, so \rulename{u-unwrap} is strongly confluent,
  and therefore by \cref{lem:strong} is confluent.
\end{proof}

To see that \rulename{u-unwrap} is not Noetherian, observe that
$$\ensuremath{|mu x (tup (1,x))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}}  |tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} |tup (1, (tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} \cdots}$$
is an unending sequence of reduction steps.

\subsubsection{Information Content}

We define a second grammar, for a second language $\vcOmega$, by adding one more value |Omega|, which indicates a lack of information as to just what will be computed.
When |Omega| appears in a context where only a value is permitted, it indicates uncertainty as to what value will be provided; 
when |Omega| appears in a context where any expression is permitted, it furthermore indicates uncertainty as to how many values will be provided (possibly none).
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x| \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \vb |Omega| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}

Moreover, we add a new kind of expression |?e|, which explicitly indicates a lack of information as to whether |e| might be replaced by |fail| because of the failure of an
expression or equation in some execution context containing |e|; it furthermore indicates uncertainty as to whether any of its free variables might be unified with some
value.

\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
        \text{Expressions}   & e     & ::= & |v| \vb |eq ; e| \vb |def x e| \vb |fail|
                                           \vb |e_1 choice e_2| \vb |apply1N v_1 v_2|
                             \vb |one e| \vb |all e| \vb |?e| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}


For every term of \versecalc{} there is a corresponding term of $\vcOmega$, identical in structure and appearance and containing no occurrence of |Omega| or |?|;
we identify such terms and regard the set of terms of \versecalc{} as simply a subset of the terms of $\vcOmega$.

The definition of substitution (\cref{fig:substitution}) is extended in the expected trivial manner: $|subst Omega x v| \equiv |Omega|$ and $|subst (?e) x v| \equiv |?(subst e x v)|$.

\begin{definition}
(after \cite[Definition 2.3]{ariola:skew-confluence})
Let |T| be a set of terms over a signature that includes the constant |Omega|.
Define $\urleqomegaof{T}$ to be the relation such that $|Omega| \urleqomegaof{T} |M|$ for every term $|M| \in |T|$;
then define $\leqomegaof{T}$ to be the transitive, reflexive, and compatible closure of $\urleqomegaof{T}$.
\end{definition}


\begin{definition}
(compare \cite[Definition 2.3]{ariola:skew-confluence})
Let |T| be a set of terms over a signature that includes the constant |Omega|, and for every term |M| in |T| also includes the term |?M|.
%Assume that in every term, every bound variable has been renamed by $\alpha$-conversion so as to be distinct from every free variable.

First define $\urleqomegaof{T}$ to be the primitive relation such that
\begin{center}
$\begin{array}{l}
\forall |M| \in |T| \suchthat |Omega| \urleqomegaof{T} |M| \\
\forall |M| \in |T| \suchthat {|?M|} \urleqomegaof{T} |M| \\
\forall |M| \in |T| \suchthat {|?M|} \urleqomegaof{T} |fail| \\
\forall |M|, |N| \in |T| \suchthat (|M| \urleqomegaof{T} |N|) \implies (|?M| \urleqomegaof{T} |?N|) \\
\forall |M| \in |T| \suchthat \forall |v| \in \freevars{M} \suchthat {|?M|} \urleqomegaof{T} |subst (?M) v Omega| \text{\quad DO WE NEED THIS??} \\
\end{array}$
\end{center}
This primitive relation is a quasiorder but not a partial order; for example,  $|Omega| \urleqomegaof{T} |?Omega|$ and $|?Omega| \urleqomegaof{T} |Omega|$,
therefore $\urleqomegaof{T}$ is not antisymmetric. To get a partial order, it is necessary to identify |?Omega| with |Omega|; it is furthermore convenient to identify |?fail| with |fail|,
to identify
|??M| with |?M| for all terms |M| in |T|, and to identify |?M| with |?N | where |N| is the result of replacing every occurrence of free variable in |M| with |Omega|.
(In effect, we are taking the quotient $|T| / \sim_T$ where $\sim_T$ is the equivalence relation defined by $(M \sim_T N) \iff (M \urleqomegaof{T} N) \logand (N \urleqomegaof{T} M)$
and then representing each equivalence class of terms by its ``simplest'' member---being as small as possible and having as few free variables as possible.)

Then define $\leqomegaof{T}$ to be the transitive, reflexive, and compatible closure of $\urleqomegaof{T}$ on this set of representative terms.
\end{definition}

