\begin{lemma}\label{lem:critpairs}\cite[Lemma 3.1]{Huet80}
The relation $\go{\rr}$ is locally confluent iff for every critical pair |(e_1, e_2)| of $\rr$, |e_1| and |e_2| can be \emph{joined}---that is, there exists |e_3| such that
 $|e_1| \gos{\rr} |e_3|$ and  $|e_2| \gos{\rr} |e_3|$.
\end{lemma}

Observe that if the two terms of a critical pair |(e_1, e_2)| are identical, they can be joined at $|e_3| = |e_1| = |e_2|$.
We say that such a critical pair is \emph{trivial}, and no separate proof of joining is required.


\begin{lemma}[$\rinfo$-Confluent] \label{lem:rinfo-c}
$\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian; therefore $\rinfo$ is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Consider all critical pairs of $\rinfo$. By inspection, we can easily see that critical pairs can arise only from left-hand-side subterms of the form |?e| or |e choice e'|, so we examine these possibilities in more detail.
\begin{itemize}
\item  Rules \rulename{info-unsure-fail} and \rulename{info-unsure-omega} produce no critical pairs.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-unsure-fail} and \rulename{info-unsure-unsure} produce the trivial critical pair |(?fail, ?fail)|. 

\item  Rules \rulename{info-unsure-omega} and \rulename{info-unsure-unsure} produce the trivial critical pair |(?Omega, ?Omega)|. 

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-fail-r} produce the trivial critical pair |(fail, fail)|. 

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce no critical pairs.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(e_2 choice e_3, fail choice (e_2 choice e_3))|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce the trivial critical pair |(Omega, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pairs |(e_1 choice e_3, e_1 choice (fail choice e_3))| and |(e_1 choice e_2, e_1 choice (e_2 choice fail))|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-choice-omega} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(Omega choice e_3, Omega choice (e_2 choice e_3)|.

\item  No other pairs of rules produce any critical pairs.
\end{itemize}
The critical pair |(e_2 choice e_3, fail choice (e_2 choice e_3))| can be joined at |e_2 choice e_3| in one step by using rule \rulename{info-fail-l} on |fail choice (e_2 choice e_3))|. 
The critical pair |(e_1 choice e_3, e_1 choice (fail choice e_3))| can be joined at |e_1 choice e_3| in one step by using rule \rulename{info-fail-l} on (a subterm of) |e_1 choice (fail choice e_3))|. 
The critical pair |(e_1 choice e_2, e_1 choice (e_2 choice fail))| can be joined at |e_1 choice e_2| in one step by using rule \rulename{info-fail-r} on (a subterm of) |e_1 choice (e_2 choice fail))|. 
The critical pair |(Omega choice e_3, Omega choice (e_2 choice e_3)| can be joined at |Omega| by using rule \rulename{info-choice-omega} on |Omega choice e_3| and on |Omega choice (e_2 choice e_3)|.
Trivial critical pairs require no separate proof of joining.

All critical pairs can be joined; therefore by \cref{lem:critpairs} $\rinfo$ is locally confluent.

Let the \emph{size} of a term of $\vcOmega$ be the sum of (i)~the number of tokens it contains other than parentheses,
and (ii)~the sum, over every subterm of the term that is a choice expression, the size of the left-hand operand of that choice expression.
Because any given term $e$ has some finite number $n$ of tokens other than parentheses and a finite number $k$ of subterms that are choice expressions,
and because the size of a subterm cannot be greater than the size of an expression, the size of $e$ cannot exceed $(k+1)n$ and therefore is finite.
Furthermore the size of a term cannot be less than zero.
It follows that every rewriting sequence from term $e$ can have no more than $(k+1)n$ steps. So $\rinfo$ is bounded and therefore Noetherian.
Each of the rewrite rules in \cref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} produces a new expression that is strictly smaller in size. 

Because $\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian, it is confluent by Newman's lemma.
\end{proof}

Because $\rinfo$ is confluent and Noetherian, it follows that $\rinfo$ defines unique normal forms for $\vcOmega$, which justifies the following definition.
\begin{definition}
Let $\omegavc(e)$ be the function that takes any term in $\vcOmega$ and returns the term that is its normal form under $\rinfo$.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}
The comparison $e \leqomegavc e'$ is defined to mean $\omegavc(e) \leqomega \omegavc(e')$.
\end{definition}

\begin{lemma}
For all terms $t$ and $t'$, $t \gos{\rinfo} t'$ implies $\omegavc(t) = \omegavc(t')$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
This follows immediately from the confluence of $\rinfo$ and the fact that $\omegavc$ returns the normal form under $\rinfo$.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
For every term $t$ and every $u \in \occ(t)$, $\omegavc(\tsubst{t}{u}{\omegavc{t/u}}) = \omegavc{t}$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  By the definition of $\omegavc$, $t/u \gos{\rinfo} \omegavc{t/u}$. Because $\gos{\rinfo}$ is compatible, it follows that $t \gos{rinfo} \tsubst{t}{u}{\omegavc{t/u}}$.
  XXX
\end{proof}



